\\",\\\"title\\\":\\\"(PDF) Withering Gongzhi: Cyber Criticism of Chinese Public Intellectuals\\\",\\\"sitename\\\":\\\"researchgate.net\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/321170521_Withering_Gongzhi_Cyber_Criticism_of_Chinese_Public_Intellectuals\\\",\\\"doc_id\\\":\\\"f6802ddcae99343f-96bb759ff07ef749\\\",\\\"index\\\":2}},{\\\"text_card\\\":{\\\"summary\\\":\\\"近日光明日报撰文为“自干五”点赞，一时间在舆论场里掀起了阵阵涟漪。该文将盛行网络的两大群体“公知”和“自干五”进行了对比，前者专找现实社会中的阴暗面进行无限放大，引用几段洋人语录就开始在网上信口雌黄，睁眼说瞎话，专挑社会和政府的不是；后者的全称为“自带干粮的五毛”，指的是那些自觉自愿为社会正能量点赞、为中国发展鼓劲的网民。“公知”、“自干五”等网络词汇得以在官方媒体上刊出，预示着官方和民间两套话语体系正在渐渐走向融合。\\\\n“公知”虽然是“公共知识分子”的简称，但在传播过程中已经逐渐异化，并被赋予了贬义色彩。今天，活跃在微博上的“公知”已经不同于鲁迅时代的“公共知识分子”，吴法天曾在回应记者采访时说过：“以受迫害心态切入，痛陈言论不自由，看到谣言就转发，批批体制骂骂大街，说几句俏皮话，然后加一句‘这个社会怎么了’就升华了，人人可以做公知！”他们大多已经褪去“公共性”的外衣，呈现其虚伪性和私利性，恰如鲁迅所说“掣维新之衣，以蔽其自私之体”。\\\\n“自干五”的出现，很大程度上是因为不满话语权被“公知”垄断，他们大胆地辟谣，抨击“公知”的错误观念，因而常被贴上“五毛”的标签，意指拿钱替政府说话的人。但事实上，“自干五”并不是政府的拥趸，而是站在一个客观、理性的角度看待当今社会问题的。他们并不是只会唱赞歌，而是既有褒扬也有批评；他们既有爱国的情感，也痛恨腐败，斥责社会不公正；对于当前社会发展状况，他们既能看到成绩，也能看到存在的问题，并且能够提出可行性的建议，而不是一味地发泄情绪。那些无视国内发展成就，始终停留在旧中国的刻板印象中，以及深陷在西方民主神话意淫中的观念，都不会是我们看待中国和世界的正确角度。\\\\n今天的“公知”将西方的言论自由奉为圭臬，但是当他们在网上无法说服别人服从自己观点的时候，他们既没有尝试理解别人的思想，也没有誓死捍卫别人说话的权利，而是强行为对方贴上“五毛”的标签。“公知”、“五毛”、“自干五”等标签化的表达，容易割裂社会认知，本质上是对多元声音的抑制。\\\\n不同声音在互联网空间里的交锋，反映了我们这个时代的进步，若一定要将“公知”、“五毛”、“自干五”割裂为不同的群体要求受众来站队，既是对自由的戕害，也违背了互联网时代的发展需要。\\\\n清朗网络空间，自然需要法治来规范，是否合法将是互联网管理的本质要求，但这也仅仅能够解决“管得住”的问题。网络空间的治理，更重要的是要传播正能量，这就需要“自干五”们承担起更多的责任。值得一提的是，正能量并不意味着拒绝批评性的声音，相反，只有批评才能促成理解，但是批评必须建立在不损害国家和人民核心利益的基础之上。除此之外，政府还要提升权力运行的透明度，利用网络便利公众监督，只要不触犯法律的民意表达都必须予以正视。\\\\n\\\",\\\"title\\\":\\\"“自干五”被污名化抑制多元表达--评论-人民网\\\",\\\"sitename\\\":\\\"中国共产党新闻网\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"http://cpc.people.com.cn/pinglun/n/2014/1118/c241220-26048448.html\\\",\\\"doc_id\\\":\\\"8cb1c0d238d9c2ee-10ceae9b1c5f076e\\\",\\\"original_doc_rank\\\":1,\\\"index\\\":3}},{\\\"text_card\\\":{\\\"summary\\\":\\\"withering gong zhi : cyber criticism of chinese public intellectuals \\\\n the international journal of communication 12 ( 2018 ) : 1966 - 1987 \\\\n 36 pages \\\\n rongbin han \\\\n department of international affairs , school of public and international affairs , university of georgia \\\\n abstract \\\\n this article explores why the term “ public intellectual ” has turned into a disgraceful label in chinese cyberspace . through examining how netizens have constructed the negative perception of “ public intellectuals , ” it shows that the internet has not only empowered regime critics , but also promoted pluralization of expression by bringing different values , beliefs and identities into contact with an unprecedented frequency and intensity . the denigration of public intellectuals illustrates the contestation between digitally expressed civility and incivility , which has yet to be sufficiently discussed . findings in this study also suggest that “ authoritarian resilience ” depends on the regime ’s adaptability as well as the dynamics between its supporters and challengers . \\\\n keywords : cyber politics , public intellectuals , discourse competition , china , authoritarian resilience , gong zhi \\\\n han , rongbin , withering gong zhi : cyber criticism of chinese public intellectuals . the international journal of communication 12 ( 2018 ) : 1966 - 1987 , available at ssrn : https : / / ssrn . com / abstract = 3151876 \\\\n rongbin han ( contact author ) \\\\n department of international affairs , school of public and international affairs , university of georgia ( email ) \\\\n 322 candler hall \\\\n athens , ga georgia 30602 - 6254 \\\\n united states \\\\n home page : http : / / han rongbin . com\\\",\\\"title\\\":\\\"Withering Gongzhi: Cyber Criticism of Chinese Public Intellectuals by Rongbin Han :: SSRN\\\",\\\"sitename\\\":\\\"papers.ssrn.com\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3151876\\\",\\\"doc_id\\\":\\\"f4d4766b93fc1d7a-c38d346ed5024195\\\",\\\"original_doc_rank\\\":1,\\\"index\\\":4}},{\\\"text_card\\\":{\\\"summary\\\":\\\"( un ) civil society in digital china | withering gong zhi : cyber criticism of chinese public intellectuals \\\\n rongbin han \\\\n abstract \\\\n this article explores why the term public intellectual has turned into a disgraceful label in chinese cyberspace . by examining how netizens have constructed the negative perception of public intellectuals , it shows that the internet has not only empowered regime critics but also promoted the pluralization of expression by bringing different values , beliefs , and identities into contact with unprecedented frequency and intensity . the denigration of public intellectuals illustrates the contest between digitally expressed civility and incivility , which has yet to be sufficiently discussed . findings in this study also suggest that authoritarian resilience depends on the regime ’s adaptability and the dynamics between its supporters and challengers . \\\\n keywords \\\\n cyber politics , public intellectuals , discourse competition , china , authoritarian resilience \\\\n full text : \\\\n pdf\\\",\\\"title\\\":\\\"(Un)civil Society in Digital China| Withering Gongzhi: Cyber Criticism of Chinese Public Intellectuals | Han | International Journal of Communication\\\",\\\"sitename\\\":\\\"ijoc.org\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://ijoc.org/index.php/ijoc/article/view/5288\\\",\\\"doc_id\\\":\\\"38c1d1466050f281-48ad8e652208fc98\\\",\\\"original_doc_rank\\\":2,\\\"index\\\":5}}],\\\"queries\\\":[\\\"The reason why the term Public Intellectual is stigmatized on the Chinese Internet\\\",\\\"中国互联网上 公知 污名化 原因\\\"],\\\"tags\\\":[\\\"11000101\\\"]}\"},\"message_id\":\"1904153965281026\",\"local_message_id\":\"aec55020-0155-11f0-a2bf-99ea6f66b78c\",\"conversation_id\":\"1918735118668034\",\"local_conversation_id\":\"local_5371222015774671\",\"section_id\":\"1918735118668290\",\"reply_id\":\"1904153965280514\",\"is_delta\":true,\"status\":4,\"input_content_type\":2001,\"message_index\":2,\"bot_id\":\"7338286299411103781\"}","event_id":"4","even